</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="497" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,1274,1731]" pageId="2" pageNumber="497">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1454,1479]" pageId="2" pageNumber="497">Remarks.</emphasis>
The Indian specimens are reported to bear a pair extraordinary organs (&quot;lateral feet&quot; of Naidu and Rao), each comprised of three adhesive tubes, while in the European specimens, these organs are composed of four tubes (
<bibRefCitation author="Marotta, R. &amp; Todaro, M. A. &amp; Ferraguti, M." box="[226,461,1526,1551]" pageId="2" pageNumber="497" pagination="111 - 119" refId="ref9150" refString="Marotta, R., Todaro, M. A. &amp; Ferraguti, M. 2008. The unique gravireceptor organs of Pleurodasys helgolandicus (Gastrotricha: Macrodasyida). Zoomorphology, 127, 111 - 119. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 00435 - 008 - 0056 - 6" type="journal article" year="2008">
Marotta 
<emphasis box="[326,377,1526,1551]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="497">et al</emphasis>
., 2008
</bibRefCitation>
). This difference, and the geographic distance from the 
<typeStatus box="[1103,1151,1527,1551]" pageId="2" pageNumber="497">type</typeStatus>
locality, call for a better morphological comparison between Indian and European populations. Ideally, such comparisons should also include genetic data as well as specimens from conspecifics, e.g., 
<taxonomicName authority="Todaro, Dal Zotto, Bownes &amp; Perissinotto, 2017" authorityName="Todaro, Dal Zotto, Bownes &amp; Perissinotto" authorityYear="2017" class="Gastrotricha (awaiting allocation)" family="Cephalodasyidae" genus="Pleurodasys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Macrodasyida" pageId="2" pageNumber="497" phylum="Gastrotricha" rank="species" species="incomptus">
<emphasis box="[929,1075,1599,1622]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="497">P. incomptus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Todaro, M. A. &amp; Dal Zotto, M. &amp; Bownes, S. J. &amp; Perissinotto, R." pageId="2" pageNumber="497" pagination="139 - 154" refId="ref10762" refString="Todaro, M. A., Dal Zotto, M., Bownes, S. J. &amp; Perissinotto, R. (2017) Two new interesting species of Macrodasyida (Gastrotricha) from KwaZulu-Natal (South Africa). Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington, 130, 139 - 154. https: // doi. org / 10.2988 / 17 - 00010" type="journal article" year="2017">Todaro, Dal Zotto, Bownes &amp; Perissinotto, 2017</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
described from 
<collectingCountry box="[543,689,1634,1659]" name="South Africa" pageId="2" pageNumber="497">South Africa</collectingCountry>
(see 
<bibRefCitation author="Todaro, M. A. &amp; Dal Zotto, M. &amp; Bownes, S. J. &amp; Perissinotto, R." box="[751,967,1634,1659]" pageId="2" pageNumber="497" pagination="139 - 154" refId="ref10762" refString="Todaro, M. A., Dal Zotto, M., Bownes, S. J. &amp; Perissinotto, R. (2017) Two new interesting species of Macrodasyida (Gastrotricha) from KwaZulu-Natal (South Africa). Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington, 130, 139 - 154. https: // doi. org / 10.2988 / 17 - 00010" type="journal article" year="2017">
Todaro 
<emphasis box="[839,890,1634,1659]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="497">et al</emphasis>
. 2017
</bibRefCitation>
). We note positively that for some of the Indian populations information on seasonal dynamics are available (
<bibRefCitation author="Govindankutty, A. G. &amp; Nair, N. B." box="[940,1272,1670,1695]" pageId="2" pageNumber="497" pagination="1 - 5" refId="ref8479" refString="Govindankutty, A. G. &amp; Nair, N. B. (1972) Observations on the breeding periods of certain interstitial nematodes, gastrotrichs and copepods of the south west coast of India. Journal of the Marine Biological Association of India, 14, 1 - 5." type="journal article" year="1972">Govindankutty &amp; Nair 1972</bibRefCitation>
). This 
<typeStatus box="[1354,1402,1671,1695]" pageId="2" pageNumber="497">type</typeStatus>
of information is much needed but rarely available for gastrotrich species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
